Effects of Students Background and Habits on their PISA Scores¶

by Rubén Vilela Freire¶

Investigation Overview¶

The aim of this research was to find out which factors have the greatest influence on a student's grade. The main focus was placed on the family context, time invested, immigration and psychological factors.

Dataset Overview¶

This document explores the 2012 PISA report dataset, which contains data, approximately 485000 observations, related to the preparation of students for real-life challenges. In addition to several indicators to evaluate the family context, time spent, immigration and psychological factors, data corresponding to the gender of the students has been included.

Distribution of the Scores¶

The overall score presents a normal distribution centered approximately at 500 points out of 1000.

Distribution of Learning Time¶

Learning time shows a normal distribution with an average of 11 hours of study per week. Although the majority study between 0 and 20 hours per week, there are students who study up to 40 hours per week.

How much does family possessions affect the score?¶

It is observed that there is a positive relationship between the students' overall grade and the number of possessions their families have. The difference in overall score between the poorest and the richest students is approximately 200 points.

How does learning time affect the scores?¶

Learning time and students' overall grade also show a positive relationship, although this is weaker than in the case of possessions. The expected score difference between students who do not study any hours per week and those who study more than 30 hours per week, is 100 points.

Does parents' studies affect students?¶

In general terms, it is observed that the higher the educational qualifications of the parents, the better the overall score of the students. The difference between extremes, i.e., between no parental education and university education, is about 100 points.

How do social class and learning time interact with the overall score?¶

  • Social class, measured as the number of belongings at home, affects the student's overall score, with a difference of almost 100 points between the high and low social class. The average difference between the high and middle class is 40 points.
  • More study time improves the student's score as long as this time does not exceed 20 hours per week. The most efficient weekly amount of study is between 5 and 20 hours, with only a 20-point variation.

How do the social class and the educational level of the parents interact with the overall score?¶

  • A higher level of education has a positive impact on the student's overall score in the middle and upper social classes. However, in the lower social class, the maximum grade peak is reached with a parental education of ISCED 3B, 4.

How do the educational level of parents and immigration interact with the overall score?¶

  • Although the impact of parents' educational background is positively related to students' grades, it is more influential in families with native-born parents. In the case of parents with an educational level up to ISCED 2, students with second-generation immigrant parents show better test scores.
